VOCAB!---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Statistical Tests:
Use Data from a sample to assess a claim about a population
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Null Hypothesis, H0:
This is the claim that there is no effect or no difference in the Statistical data (This will always us an "=" sign)
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Alternative Hypothesis, Ha:
This is the claim that we are trying to find significant Statistical evidence for. (This will always use inequality signs or not equal signs)
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Statistical Significance:
When reults as extreme as the observed sample statistic are unlikely to occur by random change alone 
(assuming that null hypothesis is true), we say the sample results are Statisticaly significant.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
P-value:
The p-value of the sample data in a statistical test is the probability, when the null hypothesis is true, of obtaining a sample as extreme 
(or more extreme than) the observed value

The smaller the p-value, the stronger the statistical evidence is against the null hypothesis and in favor of the alternative

A formal way to measure the strength of evidence a smaple provides against the null hypothesis and in support of the alternative hypothesis
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Randomization Distribution:

Randomization Distribution simulate many samples using a random process that matches the way the original data was collected and that assumes
the null hypothesis is true. Collect the values of a sample statistic for each sample to create a Randomization. 

Assess the Significance of the original sample by determining where its sample statistic lies in the randomization distribution.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Significance level "Alpha":

The significance level, a, for a test of hypothesis is a boundary below which we can conclude that a p-value shows
Statisticaly significant evidence against the null hypothesis.
Common Significance levels are a = 0.05 (5%), a = 0.01 (1%), or a = .10 (10%).
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Type 1 Errors:
Rejecting a true H0 (A false positive - Saying Ha is true when it is not)
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Type 2 Errors:
Failing to reject, or not rejecting a false H0 (A false negative - Saying H0 is a false when it is not)
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Bootstrap is for when you need to know if there is a difference or if something is happening

Randomization is for when you want to know how strong of a difference there is.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Normal Distribution: A distribution that is both symmetric and bell-shaped
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Normal Density Curve: A normal distribution follows a bell-shaped curve.
We use the two parameters mena, u, and standard deviation, o, to distinguish
one normal curve from another. We write N(u, o) to specify that a distribution is normal (N)
with some mean (u) and a standard deviation.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Standard Normal: The standard normal has  amean zero and a standard deviation of one
to convert any X~N(u, o) to Z~N(0 , 1) we standardize values with the z-score.
Z = (x-u)/o

to convert the other way use:

X = u + Zo
:)
